1705: JS Bach, aged 20, walks 400 km/250 miles from Arnstadt to Lubeck in autumntime.

1903: C. Brancusi, aged 27, walks 2500 km/1600 miles from Romania to Paris, taking him 18 months to walk through Europe.

Baron Julius Evola suggested his students to try the latter's feat too.

"You are young.¬† At your age, you can sleep in the open, under the arches of a bridge. Brancusi, the great Romanian sculptor walked all the way from Romania to Paris. Good training. Just imagine the thoughts, the experience he would have gained during his walks." - Evola.

I often think nowadays about Henry Jenkins, the 17th century English fisherman, who lived to 169 years of age. Born in 1501, died in 1670. There were a few other centenarians in his parish and they said "he was an elderly man ever since they knew him". Probably outlived them too.

Imagine you are a child and there is an old man in your church and you grow and slowly become an old man yourself but he just keeps living. Dr. Ray Peat joked that ideally people should start puberty around the age of 70-80. No one even suspects the scale of human potentialities.

Sir John Floyer who described the Englishman attributed his longevity to waddling and swimming in water streams and rivers so that's a good hobby to get into. Also all other cases he mentions involve ~115 year old men starting to regrow hair and teeth and keeping sexual function.

"I think [mechanical] technology is so simple compared to the organism." - Ray Peat

Same as Leibniz writing that machines are always inefficient because a machine is a mineral on the microscopical scale, while with living beings scale infinitely no matter how much you "zoom in".

Like with the machine you have one level of complexity. A structure that's made of metal. But with animals you have infinite levels of organs, tissues, cells/"corpuscles", organelles, etc. scaling down to the monad without losing the same principles of rational organization.
It just never gets above the "wooden leg" level
